<Document>
<name>Cradle Mountain &amp; West Coast — Devonport to Hobart</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Cradle Mountain &amp; West Coast — Devonport to Hobart</h2><p><i>Tasmania, Australia · Devonport to Hobart via Cradle Mountain, Strahan, Lake St Clair</i></p><p><b>440 km through Tasmania's wildest country — ancient rainforest, glacial lakes, Macquarie Harbour, and the Lyell Highway.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>375 km (233 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–4 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>November–April for full hiking; year-round drivable but very wet (the west receives 3,000+ mm of rain annually)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Rain — constantly; narrow shoulders on the Lyell Highway switchbacks; wallabies and devils at dusk; tannin-stained rivers; isolation</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>646</td></tr></table><hr><p>The west of Tasmania is wild Gondwana — Huon pine that lives 3,000 years, Tasmanian myrtle and leatherwood, tannin-stained rivers running the color of black tea. Cradle Mountain is the northern gateway to the Tasmanian Wilderness World Heritage Area, 1.6 million hectares of largely roadless country. The Overland Track from here south is one of the world's great walks; the 6 km Dove Lake circuit is the easy taste. Strahan, on Macquarie Harbour, was the supply port for the convict settlement at Sarah Island (1822–33), Australia's most brutal penal station. From there the Lyell Highway climbs the Mount Lyell mining country (Queenstown's lunar landscape is the legacy of a century of copper smelting) and crosses the central highlands to the Derwent Valley and Hobart.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Sheffield</b> — 'Town of Murals.' 60+ outdoor murals tell the story of pioneer settlement; an annual mural-painting festival keeps the collection growing.</li><li><b>Dove Lake / Cradle Mountain</b> — 6 km flat circuit around the lake with the iconic Cradle Mountain dolerite peak rising behind. Boardwalks the entire way. Shuttle bus from the visitor centre is mandatory in peak season.</li><li><b>Strahan</b> — Sarah Island convict settlement reached by Gordon River cruise from the harbour. The Huon pines along the Gordon take 50 years to grow as wide as a finger; some living trees here are 2,500+ years old.</li><li><b>Queenstown</b> — Conical bare hills around the town are the visible legacy of 100 years of copper smelting (1893–1994) — sulphur dioxide killed the rainforest, rain washed soil down to bedrock. Slow regrowth now in progress.</li><li><b>Franklin–Gordon Wild Rivers NP</b> — Crossed by the Lyell Highway. The 1983 High Court decision stopping a hydro dam on the Franklin River was a turning point in Australian environmental history.</li><li><b>Lake St Clair</b> — 187 m-deep glacial lake, southern terminus of the Overland Track. Boat taxi to Narcissus Hut; rainforest boardwalk loops near the visitor centre.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
